Barn: Margareta f. 21, Jan Fredrik 25. — Stud:-ex. i Sthlm 04, stud. v. KTH 04-05, fil. kand. i Upps. 12, fil. lic. 14, fil dr 17. Stud:res. t. BrasiUen 20-21 o. t. ett flert. europ. länder. translated: Enquist, Fredrik Karl, Ph.D., Professor, Gothenburg, b. March 16, 1885 in Stockholm, son of mining engineer Fredrik Leon. Engaged to Fredrique Quennerstedt. Married in 1920 to Greta Ekecrantz, who have two children: Margareta, born in 1921, and Jan Fredrik, born in 1925. Fredrik obtained his high school degree in Stockholm in 1904 and studied at KTH from 1904-1905. He earned a Bachelor's Degree in Philosophy in Uppsala in 1912, a Master's Degree in Philosophy in 1914, and a Ph.D. in Philosophy in 1917. He went on to study in Brazil from 1920-1921, as well as multiple European countries. He was a lecturer in physical geography at Uppsala from 1917-1938 and a professor of geography, including commercial geography and ethnography, at the University of Gothenburg from 1938. He authored several scientific papers, including "The Influence of Wind on the Distribution of Glaciers" (academic thesis, 1916). He is a member of the Swedish National Committee for Geography and the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences.
